CMPO:0000002.name: cell population phenotype
CMPO:0000002.description: A quality that that inheres in a population of cells

CMPO:0000003.name: cellular phenotype
CMPO:0000003.description: A quality that inheres in or specifically depends on a cellular process, a cell population, a whole cell or a subcellular structure.

CMPO:0000005.name: cell morphology phenotype
CMPO:0000005.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in the whole cell relating to the cell's shape, size or structure

CMPO:0000007.name: cell process phenotype
CMPO:0000007.description: A quality that inheres in a cellular process

CMPO:0000008.name: cell component number phenotype
CMPO:0000008.description: An increase or decrease in the number of specified components within a cell

CMPO:0000010.name: cell component size phenotype
CMPO:0000010.description: A collection of size qualities that inhere in a cellular component

CMPO:0000011.name: cell component shape phenotype
CMPO:0000011.description: A collection of shape qualities that inhere in a cellular component

CMPO:0000012.name: cell component structure phenotype
CMPO:0000012.description: A collection of structure qualities that inhere in a cellular component

CMPO:0000013.name: cell viability phenotype
CMPO:0000013.description: A phenotype relating to the ability of a cell survive or to develop normally

CMPO:0000014.name: viable cell phenotype
CMPO:0000014.description: A cell phenotype where the cell is viable

CMPO:0000015.name: inviable cell phenotype
CMPO:0000015.description: A cell phenotype where the cell is not viable

CMPO:0000016.name: cell nucleation phenotype
CMPO:0000016.description: A nucleation quality that inheres in the whole cell

CMPO:0000018.name: multinucleated cell phenotype
CMPO:0000018.description: A multinucleate quality that inheres in a cell

CMPO:0000020.name: cytoskeletal phenotype
CMPO:0000020.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in any constituent part of the cytoskeleton, a cellular scaffolding or skeleton that maintains cell shape, enables some cell motion (using structures such as flagella and cilia), and plays important roles in both intra-cellular transport (e.g. the movement of vesicles and organelles) and cellular division. Includes constituent parts of intermediate filaments, microfilaments, microtubules, and the microtrabecular lattice.

CMPO:0000021.name: endoplasmic reticulum phenotype
CMPO:0000021.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in any constituent part of the endoplasmic reticulum, the irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae.

CMPO:0000022.name: golgi phenotype
CMPO:0000022.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in  any constituent part of the Golgi apparatus, a compound membranous cytoplasmic organelle of eukaryotic cells, consisting of flattened, ribosome-free vesicles arranged in a more or less regular stack

CMPO:0000023.name: mitochondrion phenotype
CMPO:0000023.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in  any constituent part of a mitochondrion, a semiautonomous, self replicating organelle that occurs in varying numbers, shapes, and sizes in the cytoplasm of virtually all eukaryotic cells.

CMPO:0000024.name: nuclear phenotype
CMPO:0000024.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in  any constituent part of the nucleus, a membrane-bounded organelle of eukaryotic cells in which chromosomes are housed and replicated.

CMPO:0000026.name: organelle shape phenotype
CMPO:0000026.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in  a cellular organelle relating to the organelle's shape

CMPO:0000027.name: nucleus shape phenotype
CMPO:0000027.description: A collection of qualities that inhere in  the nucleus relating to the ratios of distances between its features (points, edges, surfaces and also holes etc).

CMPO:0000028.name: cell adhesion phenotype
CMPO:0000028.description: A phenotype where the attachment of a cell, either to another cell or to an underlying substrate such as the extracellular matrix, via cell adhesion molecules is observed

CMPO:0000029.name: cell cycle phenotype
CMPO:0000029.description: A collection of qualities that inhere the cell cycle

CMPO:0000030.name: cell death phenotype
CMPO:0000030.description: A phenotype where the cell death process process is observed

CMPO:0000032.name: cell membrane organisation phenotype
CMPO:0000032.description: A phenotype observation of a process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a membrane. A membrane is a double layer of lipid molecules that encloses all cells, and, in eukaryotes, many organelles; may be a single or double lipid bilayer; also includes associated proteins.

CMPO:0000033.name: cell migration phenotype
CMPO:0000033.description: A phenotype of a cell involving its translation from one location to another

CMPO:0000035.name: cell growth phenotype
CMPO:0000035.description: A phenotype observation of the process in which a cell irreversibly increases in size over time by accretion and biosynthetic production of matter similar to that already present.

CMPO:0000036.name: chromosome segregation phenotype
CMPO:0000036.description: A phenotype observation of the process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized into specific structures and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets. In eukaryotes, chromosome segregation begins with the alignment of chromosomes at the metaphase plate, includes chromosome separation, and ends when chromosomes have completed movement to the spindle poles.

CMPO:0000037.name: metabolic process phenotype
CMPO:0000037.description: A phenotype observation of chemical reactions and pathways, including anabolism and catabolism, by which living organisms transform chemical substances. Metabolic processes typically transform small molecules, but also include macromolecular processes such as DNA repair and replication, and protein synthesis and degradation.

CMPO:0000038.name: organelle localization phenotype
CMPO:0000038.description: A phenotype observations where any process in which an organelle is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.

CMPO:0000039.name: regulation of metabolic process phenotype
CMPO:0000039.description: A phenotype observation where a process modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways within a cell or an organism.

CMPO:0000040.name: regulation of signal transduction phenotype
CMPO:0000040.description: A phenotype observation of a process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction.

CMPO:0000041.name: transport phenotype
CMPO:0000041.description: A phenotype observation of the directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

CMPO:0000042.name: increased cell component number phenotype
CMPO:0000042.description: An increased number of specified cellular components relative to normal

CMPO:0000043.name: decreased cell component number phenotype
CMPO:0000043.description: A decrease in number of specified cellular components relative to normal

CMPO:0000047.name: apoptotic DNA fragmentation phenotype
CMPO:0000047.description: A phenotype observation where the cleavage of DNA during apoptosis, which usually occurs in two stages: cleavage into fragments of about 50 kbp followed by cleavage between nucleosomes to yield 200 bp fragments.

CMPO:0000048.name: apoptotic cell shape phenotype
CMPO:0000048.description: A phenotype observation at the level of the cell shape where the cell is apoptotic

CMPO:0000049.name: aggregated cells in population
CMPO:0000049.description: Groups of cells gathered or tending to gather into a mass or whole.

CMPO:0000054.description: A population of cells where a specifcied biological process is occuring or is observed.
